line ammonia-rich Strecker conditions. As with other pathways, the final hydrolysis is plausible though simplified.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State that this route depends on prior glycolaldehyde generation and concentration.\",\n        \"Include explicit mineral context for sulfite/bisulfite storage and release.\",\n        \"Refine the serine aminonitrile hydrolysis step to account for intermediate amide formation if desired.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.58\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.48,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.52,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.6,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.62,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.55,\n      \"feedback\": \"The literature does report serine detection in spark discharge residues, but the route is low-selectivity, low-yield, and the serine signal itself is treated cautiously due to possible contamination/L-enrichment concerns. As written, rxn_011 is oversimplified and also appears to omit key gas components such as CH4 and H2S that were central in the cited experiment.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Revise rxn_011 to reflect the actual experimental gas mixture and its status as a complex product distribution rather than a direct stoichiometric step.\",\n        \"Treat this pathway as auxiliary feedstock generation or low-level deposition, not a primary serine synthesis route.\",\n        \"Explicitly note uncertainty and contamination concerns from the literature.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.38\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.34,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.4,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.5,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0