uding serine after warming and hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Bernstein et al. (2002) irradiated H2O:CH3OH:NH3:HCN mixed ices at about 15 K and detected racemic serine after hydrolysis. This node represents exogenous delivery into surface inventories and corrects the previously overcompressed representation by explicitly including the mixed-ice context and hydrolysis requirement (Bernstein et al., 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Phosphorylation/activation of serine in concentrated prebiotic pools", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "drying-heating with phosphate-rich salts; activation step included for downstream condensation"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative phosphorylation activates serine for subsequent condensation chemistry.", "reasoning": "This is a necessary connecting step beyond the serine-specific literature to show how formed serine enters broader prebiotic assembly. It is speculative relative to the cited serine papers but consistent with standard prebiotic phosphorylation logic in drying phosphate-rich environments; included solely to connect serine to biochemical network use."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Wet-dry peptide condensation of serine to serylserine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces or concentrated pools"}, "mechanism": "Activated serine condenses with serine during dehydration cycles to form a dipeptide.", "reasoning": "Included as a downstream prebiotic assembly step to demonstrate biochemical integration of serine once formed. This step is more general prebiotic peptide chemistry rather than serine-specific literature and is marked as a network-completion reaction."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct bisulfite-enabled Strecker route", "description": "Surface glycolaldehyde is stabilized by bisulfite, released under alkaline conditions, and converted with ammonia and cyanide to serine aminonitrile, then hydrolyzed to serine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic to direct Strecker serine", "description": "HCN and sulfide photochemistry generates glycolaldehyde, which enters the direct Strecker route to serine aminonitrile and then serine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "UV cyanometallate equilibrium route to serine aminonitrile", "description": "HCN photoredox chemistry produces glycolonitrile and glycolaldehyde; glycolonitrile-derived network equilibria feed serine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to serine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Bisulfite-trapped cyanometallate route", "description": "UV cyanometallate-generated glycolaldehyde is first trapped as a bisulfite adduct, then released and funneled into alkaline Strecker chemistry to serine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Formamide N-formyl-serine nitrile route", "description": "Glycolaldehyde and cyanide in formamide give N-formyl-serine nitrile, whose alkaline hydrolysis yields serine-containing mixtures including serine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cyanosulfidic plus formamide route", "description": "Cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies glycolaldehyde, which in formamide with cy