r hydrothermal route.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add more explicit environmental cycling language: UV production, mineral trapping, alkaline release, then hydrolysis\",\n        \"If possible, annotate yields or branching based on cited experiments\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.89,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway aligns very well with Green et al. (2023). Formation of N-formyl-serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde and cyanide in formamide is directly supported, as is branching to dehydroalanine-type nitriles. The hydrolysis step appropriately yields a mixture containing serine rather than implying quantitative clean conversion. This is one of the most literature-faithful routes in the network.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_015\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Separate target-achievement from downstream peptide chemistry to avoid conflating route success with later assembly\",\n        \"Include explicit note that hydrolysis gives mixtures of formylated/unformylated products including serine\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.89,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.89,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hybrid pathway is plausible and uses the literature-supported idea that cyanosulfidic networks can furnish glycolaldehyde and cyanide inventories that then feed formamide chemistry. The main weakness is environmental handoff: the transition from aqueous UV cyanosulfidic conditions to concentrated formamide-rich chemistry is plausible but should be justified more explicitly by evaporation/concentration or localized formamide microenvironments.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State the concentration or drying process that connects cyanosulfidic chemistry to formamide-mediated reaction conditions\",\n        \"Clarify whether formamide is produced endogenously or delivered as a pre-existing reservoir\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.52,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.8,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is conceptually connected but weakened by the hydrothermal feedstock step. The literature specifically warns that HCN and formaldehyde activities are extremely low in hydrothermal systems and that thermal degradation is a major problem. Treating hydrothermal systems as a limited feedstock source is acceptable, but rxn_002 is too strong and insufficiently constrained relative to the literature. The downstream surface bisulfite/Strecker chemistry is robust.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Downgrade hydrothermal production to speculative low-flux feedstock generation with explicit concentration bottlenecks\",\n        \"Add export to cooler mixing zones or mineral adsorption before surface processing\",\n        \"Avoid implying substantial direct hydrothermal HCN/formaldehyde production\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.52,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.75,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.8,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.89,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"The formamide branch is strong, but the hydrothermal export premise remains the weak link. Literature does not support robust hydrothermal generation of the required HCN/glycolaldehyde inventory at useful concentrations; instead it emphasizes concentration limits and decomposition. This pathway would be stronger if it started from surface photochemical feedstocks instead of hydrothermal ones.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace hydrothermal feedstock origin with UV cyanometallate or cyanosulfidic feedstocks\",\n        \"If retaining hydrothermal input, frame it as indirect redox support rather than direct precursor production\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.68\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.66,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.7,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.74,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.76,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n      \"feedback\": \"The pathway reflects the Parker et al. spark-discharge literature in that serine can appear in a complex atmospheric product mixture. However, literature support is cautious: serine abundance is low and possible contamination/enantiomeric issues were noted. As a one-step direct route to target, it is valid only as a low-confidence auxiliary source, not a strong core synthesis pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problemat